{"title_page": "Chao pho", "text_new": "'''''Chao pho''''' ([[Thai alphabet|Thai]]: \u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e48\u0e2d, \u201cgodfather\u201d) is a term used in [[Thailand]] to describe Thai organised crime groups.\n\n==Meaning of the term==\n''Chao pho'' or ''jao poh'' literally means \u201cgodfather.\u201d Chao pho, mostly based in the provinces, have business interests in both legitimate and criminal activities. Moreover, they have groups of associates and followers, move closely with powerful bureaucrats, policemen and military figures, sit in positions in local administration, and play a key role in parliamentary elections.<ref>https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/213310.pdf</ref>\n''Chao pho'' are mostly of [[Thai Chinese|Chinese]] ethnicity.\n\n==Activities==\nAccording to Thai authorities, there are ''chao pho'' groups in 39 of [[Provinces of Thailand|Thailand's 77 provinces]]. From these provinces they work like a local [[mafia]] as they are active in both illegal as well as some legitimate businesses. They are involved in a wide range of criminal activities such as [[prostitution]], [[drug trafficking]], [[illegal gambling]] and others. They are known for cooperating with the ''[[Red Wa]]'' (who are associated with the [[United Wa State Army]]) for the trafficking and sale of narcotics.<ref>https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/213310.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Saopha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Organized crime groups in Asia}}\n\n[[Category:Organised crime groups in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Thai words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Chinese secret societies]]\n[[Category:Triad]]\n\n{{Thailand-stub}}\n{{crime-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''''Chao pho''''' ([[Thai alphabet|Thai]]: \u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e48\u0e2d, \u201cgodfather\u201d) is a term used in [[Thailand]] to describe Thai organised crime groups.\n\n==Meaning of the term==\n''Chao pho'' or ''jao poh'' literally means \u201cgodfather.\u201d Chao pho, mostly based in the provinces, have business interests in both legitimate and criminal activities. Moreover, they have groups of associates and followers, move closely with powerful bureaucrats, policemen and military figures, sit in positions in local administration, and play a key role in parliamentary elections.<ref>https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/213310.pdf</ref>\n''Chao pho'' are mostly of [[Thai Chinese|Chinese]] ethnicity.\n\n==Activities==\nAccording to Thai authorities, there are ''chao pho'' groups in 39 of [[Provinces of Thailand|Thailand\u2019s 77 provinces]]. From these provinces they work like a local [[mafia]] as they are active in both illegal as well as some legitimate businesses. They are involved in a wide range of criminal activities such as [[prostitution]], [[drug trafficking]], [[illegal gambling]] and others. They are known for cooperating with the ''[[Red Wa]]'' (who are associated with the [[United Wa State Army]]) for the trafficking and sale of narcotics.<ref>https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/213310.pdf</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Saopha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Organized crime groups in Asia}}\n\n[[Category:Organised crime groups in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Thai words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Chinese secret societies]]\n[[Category:Triad]]\n\n{{Thailand-stub}}\n{{crime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActivities:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chao_pho"}
{"title_page": "Battersea Mystery", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=March 2018}}\n{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n{{use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe '''Battersea Mystery''' is the name given to two [[List of unsolved deaths|unsolved murders]] that took place in [[London]] in 1873\u201374.<ref>R Michael Gordon: ''The Thames Torso Murders of Victorian London'', 2002</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 1873, the left quarter of a woman's trunk was discovered by a Thames Police patrol near [[Battersea]]. Subsequently, a right breast was found at [[Nine Elms]], a head at [[Limehouse]], a left forearm at Battersea, a pelvis at [[Woolwich]], until an almost complete body of a dismembered woman had been found. The nose and the chin had been cut from the face, and the head had been scalped.\n\nUnder the leadership of the Acting Chief Surgeon, Metropolitan Police, [[Thomas Bond (British physician)|Thomas Bond]], the corpse was reconstructed. The attempts to identify the remains were disturbed by the curiosity of the public, and the police first showed a photograph to any potential witness.\n\nThe Lancet reported: \"Contrary to the popular opinion, the body had not been hacked, but dexterously cut up; the joints have been opened, and the bones neatly disarticulated, even the complicated joints at the ankle and the elbow, and it is only at the articulations of the hip-joint and shoulder that the bones have been sawn through.\"\n\nThe jury passed a verdict of \"Wilful murder against some person or persons unknown\". The case remained unsolved, in spite of a \u00a3200 reward being offered for information.\n\nIn June 1874, the dismembered body of a female was discovered in the [[River Thames]] at [[Putney]]. The corpse lacked head, both arms and one leg, and had been treated with lime before being thrown in the river. The jury returned an open verdict. The case remained unsolved.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.casebook.org/dissertations/thames-torso-murders.html Inquest into the death]\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n[[Category:1873 crimes]]\n[[Category:1873 in London]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:1874 crimes]]\n[[Category:1874 in London]]\n[[Category:1874 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1873]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1874]]\n[[Category:History of the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Unidentified murder victims in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in London]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:September 1873 events]]\n[[Category:June 1874 events]]\n[[Category:19th century in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:1870s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=March 2018}}\n{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n{{use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe '''Battersea Mystery''' is the name given to two [[List of unsolved deaths|unsolved murders]] that took place in [[London]] in 1873-74.<ref>R Michael Gordon: ''The Thames Torso Murders of Victorian London'', 2002</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 1873, the left quarter of a woman's trunk was discovered by a Thames Police patrol near [[Battersea]]. Subsequently, a right breast was found at [[Nine Elms]], a head at [[Limehouse]], a left forearm at Battersea, a pelvis at [[Woolwich]], until an almost complete body of a dismembered woman had been found. The nose and the chin had been cut from the face, and the head had been scalped.\n\nUnder the leadership of the Acting Chief Surgeon, Metropolitan Police, [[Thomas Bond (British physician)|Thomas Bond]], the corpse was reconstructed. The attempts to identify the remains were disturbed by the curiosity of the public, and the police first showed a photograph to any potential witness.\n\nThe Lancet reported: \"Contrary to the popular opinion, the body had not been hacked, but dexterously cut up; the joints have been opened, and the bones neatly disarticulated, even the complicated joints at the ankle and the elbow, and it is only at the articulations of the hip-joint and shoulder that the bones have been sawn through.\"\n\nThe jury passed a verdict of \"Wilful murder against some person or persons unknown\". The case remained unsolved, in spite of a \u00a3200 reward being offered for information.\n\nIn June 1874, the dismembered body of a female was discovered in the [[River Thames]] at [[Putney]]. The corpse lacked head, both arms and one leg, and had been treated with lime before being thrown in the river. The jury returned an open verdict. The case remained unsolved.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.casebook.org/dissertations/thames-torso-murders.html Inquest into the death]\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n[[Category:1873 crimes]]\n[[Category:1873 in London]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:1874 crimes]]\n[[Category:1874 in London]]\n[[Category:1874 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1873]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1874]]\n[[Category:History of the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Unidentified murder victims in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in London]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:September 1873 events]]\n[[Category:June 1874 events]]\n[[Category:19th century in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:1870s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1873-74 \u2192 1873\u201374", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battersea_Mystery"}
{"title_page": "List of terrorist incidents", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{terrorism}}\n{{See also|List of major terrorist incidents|Number of terrorist incidents by country}}\n\n[[File:Terrorist incidents worldwide.svg|260px|thumb|right|Number of terrorist incidents by a country|Number of terrorist incidents worldwide<ref name=globalterrorismdb_0718dist>[[National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism]]. (2018). [[Global Terrorism Database]] ([https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/contact/ globalterrorismdb_0718dist.xlsx] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710191739/http://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/contact/ |date=10 July 2016 }}). Retrieved from https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd University of Maryland</ref>\n<ref name=gtd1993_0718dist>[[National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism]]. (2018). [[Global Terrorism Database]] ([https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/contact/ gtd1993_0718dist.xlsx] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710191739/http://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/contact/ |date=10 July 2016 }}). Retrieved from https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd University of Maryland</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Terrorism deaths per year by country.jpg|thumb|260px|Terrorism deaths per year by country]]\n\nThe following is a '''list of terrorist incidents''' that have not been carried out by a [[State (polity)|state]] or its forces (see [[state terrorism]] and [[state-sponsored terrorism]]). Assassinations are listed at [[List of assassinated people]].\n\n[[Definitions of terrorism]] vary, so incidents listed here are restricted to those that are [[Notability in the English Wikipedia|notable]] and described as \"terrorism\" by a consensus of [[WP:Reliable sources|reliable sources]].\n\n==Pre-1800==\nScholars dispute what might be called [[History of terrorism#Early terrorism|terrorism in earlier periods]]. The modern sense of terrorism emerged in the mid-19th century.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/recent/sept_11/changing_faces_02.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 History \u2013 The Changing Faces of Terrorism|date=|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Type\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" | Dead\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" | Injured\n!Location\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Details\n!Perpetrator\n!Part of<br />\n|-\n|5 November 1605\n|Attempted bombing\n|0\n|0\n|{{flag|England}}\n|[[Gunpowder Plot]]: A group of [[Catholic Church in England and Wales|English Catholics]] led by [[Robert Catesby]] plotted to bomb the [[House of Lords]] in order to kill [[James VI and I|King James I]], with the goal of installing his nine-year-old daughter [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] as the Catholic head of state.  The explosives beneath the House of Lords were discovered a day before their planned detonation, and the conspirators were either killed in a battle at [[Holbeche House]] or executed for treason.\n|[[Robert Catesby]] and co-conspirators\n|\n|}\n\n== 1800\u20131899 ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Type\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" | Dead\n!data-sort-type=\"number\" | Injured\n!Location\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Details\n!Perpetrator\n!Part of<br />\n|-\n|28 July 1835\n|Shooting\n|18\n|22 (+1)\n|{{flag|France}}\n|[[Giuseppe Marco Fieschi]] used a [[volley gun]] to attack the royal entourage of King [[Louis-Philippe]] of France during the annual review of the [[National Guard (France)|National Guard]] as part of a revolutionary plot.  Fieschi was badly injured when four of the weapon's barrels exploded and was captured soon after.  He was executed with co-conspirators Pierre Morey and Theodore P\u00e9pin on 19 February 1836. \n|[[Giuseppe Marco Fieschi]]\n|\n|-\n|14 April 1865\n|[[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|Assassination]], shooting, killing\n|1\n|8 (+1)\n|{{flag|United States|1865}} \n|President [[Abraham Lincoln]] was assassinated by [[John Wilkes Booth]] at Ford's Theatre in Washington D.C.  Booth's co-conspirators were to launch simultaneous attacks on Vice President [[Andrew Johnson]] and Secretary of State [[William H. Seward]], but Seward's attacker failed to kill him and Johnson's lost his nerve.  Booth was killed after a 12-day manhunt, and several of his co-conspirators were later arrested and executed.\n|[[John Wilkes Booth]] and co-conspirators\n|[[American Civil War]]\n|-\n|1865\u20131877\n|Murders\n|c. 3,000\n|Several\n|{{flag|United States|1865}}\n|c. 3,000 [[Freedmen]] and their [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] allies are killed by the [[Ku Klux Klan]] and well-organized campaigns of violence by other local whites in a campaign of terrorist violence that weakened the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|reconstructionist governments]] in the [[Southern United States]] and helped re-establish legitimized segregation.<ref>Jonathan M. Bryant: [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-694 Ku Klux Klan in the Reconstruction Era], ''The New Georgia Encyclopedia'', 3 October 2002</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fettman |first=Eric |title=The Bloody Shirt Terror After Appomattox by Stephen Budiansky Viking Press |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/01202008/postopinion/postopbooks/they_didnt_give_a_damn_111633.htm?page=0 |work=New York Post |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref>\n|[[Ku Klux Klan]]\n|[[Reconstruction Era]]\n|-\n|13 December 1867\n|Prison escape\n|12\n|120\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|The \"Clerkenwell Outrage\": a bomb exploded next to a wall of [[Clerkenwell Prison]] as an attempt to abet the escape of an arms dealer.\n|[[Fenian]] Society\n|\n|-\n|28 December 1870\n|Attempted Assassination\n|1\n|0\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|Attack to General [[Juan Prim]], [[Prime Minister of Spain]]. He died two days later after the injuries. \n|Political adversaries \n|\n|-\n|1880\n|Attempted Assassination\n|0\n|0\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|Attemp