held a parade in anticipation of the United States' entry into World War I. During the parade, a suitcase bomb was detonated, killing ten and wounding forty.\n|[[Galleanist]] [[Anarchists]] (suspected)\n|\n|-\n|30 July 1916\n|Bombing\n|4\n|Hundreds\n|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Jersey City]], [[United States]]\n|[[Black Tom explosion]] was a planned detonation of a munitions factory at [[Black Tom Island]] in the neutral United States by Imperial German Agents that killed four and injured hundreds, as well as causing millions of dollars in damages.\n|[[Imperial Germany|Imperial German]] Agents\n| \n|-\n|16 September 1920\n|Bombing\n|38\n|300\n|{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n|[[Wall Street bombing]] killed 38 people and wounded 300 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.h-net.org/~hns/articles/2001/091701a.html |title=History News Service |publisher=H-net.org |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref>\n|[[Galleanist]] [[Anarchists]] (suspected)\n|[[Red Scare]]\n|-\n|14 October 1920\n|Bombings\n|1\n|10\n||{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Trieste]], [[Italy]]\n|In Trieste, nationalists threw six bombs at the editorial office of a Socialist newspaper, resulting in one death and ten injuries.<ref name=\"italy\">{{cite news|title=BOMB WARFARE RAGING IN ITALY |url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/10/16/102902890.html |date=15 October 1920 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-12-13}}</ref>\n|[[Italy|Italian]] [[Nationalists]]\n|\n|-\n|15 October 1920\n|Bombings\n|0\n|2\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Milan]], [[Italy]] \n|In Milan, anarchists were responsible for throwing two bombs at a hotel holding a British delegation attending the Milan International Conference; there were two injuries.<ref name=\"italy\"/>\n|[[Anarchists]]\n|\n|-\n|8 December 1920\n|Bombing\n|3\n|3\n|{{flagicon|Romania}} [[Bucharest]], [[Romania]]\n|A bomb placed by a left-wing terrorist group [[:ro:Atentatul din Senatul Rom\u00e2niei din 1920|blows up]] in the Romanian Senate, killing the Minister of Justice and two other senators. Likewise, President of the Senate and two Orthodox bishops were severely injured.\n|[[Max Goldstein]], [[Leon Lichtblau]] and Saul Ozias\n|\n|-\n|31 May 1921\n|Riot\n|39-300\n|800+\n|{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Tulsa]], [[United States]]\n|The [[Tulsa race riot]] killed at least 39 people and injured over 800.<ref name=\"Sarat2009\">{{cite book|author=Austin Sarat |title=When Law Fails: Making Sense of Miscarriages of Justice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VikeV6sDAJUC&pg=PA57 |accessdate=2013-08-14 |date=1 January 2009 |publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-6225-7 |page=57}}</ref>\n|[[Ku Klux Klan]]\n|\n|-\n|13 December 1921\n|Bombing\n|100\n|\n|{{Flagicon|Romania}} [[Bolgrad]], [[Romania]]\n|The [[Bolgrad palace bombing]] occurred when a bomb thrown by [[Bessarabia|Bessarabian separatists]] at the [[Bolgrad]] palace, killed 100 soldiers and police officers.<ref>{{cite news|title=PALACE BOMBED, 100 KILLED; Bessarabian Conspirators Accused of Outrage at Bolgard |date=14 December 1921 |work=The New York Times |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9904E7DC113EEE3ABC4C52DFB467838A639EDE |accessdate=2011-10-15}}</ref>\n|[[Bessarabia|Bessarabian separatists]]\n|[[Union of Bessarabia with Romania]]\n|-\n|31 October 1923\n|Shooting\n|1\n|1\n|{{Flagicon|Irish Free State}} [[Dublin]], [[Irish Free State]]\n|[[Far-right politics|Far-right]] extremists shot two [[Judaism|Jewish]] men as they walked across [[St Stephen's Green|St. Stephen's Green]] in [[Dublin]]. One of the men was killed.<ref name=\"Reactionary murders in Ireland\">{{Cite web|url=http://comeheretome.com/2013/06/03/reactionary-murders-in-ireland/|title=Reactionary murders in Ireland|website=Come Here To Me!|access-date=2016-03-31}}</ref>\n|[[Far-right]] extremists\n|\n|-\n|16 April 1925\n|Bombing\n|150\n|~500\n|{{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]\n|[[St Nedelya Church assault]] \u2013 The [[Bulgarian Communist Party]] (BCP) blew up the church's roof during the funeral service of General Konstantin Georgiev, who had been killed in a previous Communist assault on 14 April. 150 people, mainly from the country's political and military elite, were killed in the attack and around 500 were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Sofia+Church+Terror+Attack+Vie+for+Bulgaria+Top+Event.-a0218282242|title=Sofia Church Terror Attack Vie for Bulgaria Top Event|publisher=The Free Library|date=2010|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Bulgarian Communist Party]]\n|\n|}\n\n==1930\u20131949==\n*{{flag|France}}, 1934, 9 October: During a state visit, [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia#Assassination|Alexander I of Yugoslavia]] was assassinated by Bulgarian [[Vlado Chernozemski]], a member of the [[Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization]].\n*{{flag|Mandatory Palestine}} 1936\u201339: [[1936\u201339 Arab revolt in Palestine|1936\u201339 Arab revolt]], Palestine Arab \"gang and terrorist activities\"<ref name=\"hughes\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hughes | first1 = Matthew | year = 2009 | title = The banality of brutality: British armed forces and the repression of the Arab Revolt in Palestine, 1936\u201339 | url = http://v-scheiner.brunel.ac.uk/bitstream/2438/7251/4/The%20banality%20of%20brutality.pdf | journal = English Historical Review | volume = CXXIV | issue = 507 | pages = 314\u2013354 | doi = 10.1093/ehr/cep002 | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160221163210/http://v-scheiner.brunel.ac.uk/bitstream/2438/7251/4/The%20banality%20of%20brutality.pdf | archivedate = 21 February 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> against British colonial rule, and Jewish immigrants.\n*{{flag|Mandatory Palestine}} 1937\u201348: The [[Irgun]] are responsible for [[List of Irgun attacks|numerous attacks]] in British-mandated Palestine.\n*{{Flagu|Sweden}} 1940, 3 March: Politically motivated [[:sv:Attentatet mot Norrskensflamman|bombing]] targeted at the communist newspaper ''Norrskensflamman'' (''Northern Flame'') by various perpetrators. 5 persons were killed, 2 of which were children, along with 5 others injured.\n*{{Flagu|United States|1912}} 1940\u20131956: [[George Metesky]], the \"Mad Bomber\", places over 30 bombs in New York City in public places such as [[Grand Central Terminal]] and [[Paramount Theatre (New York City)|The Paramount Theater]], injuring ten during this period, in protest against the local electric utility. He also sends many threatening letters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/12/13/archives/mad-bomber-now-70-goes-free-today-mad-bomber-now-70-goes-free-today.html |work=The New York Times |title=Mad Bomber,' Now 70, Goes Free Today; Mad Bomber,' Now 70, Goes Free Today 37 Blasts Set Initials 'F.P.' Explained Institute Assailed |date=13 December 1973 |accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n*{{Flagu|United States|1912}} 1940, 4 July: Time bomb is recovered from the British Pavilion at the [[1939 New York World's Fair]], two policemen are killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=POLICE DIE IN BLAST; Timed Device Explodes After it is Taken out of Pavilion |date= 5 July 1940 |work=The New York Times |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D02EFDA123EE432A25756C0A9619C946193D6CF |accessdate=2015-03-05}}</ref>\n* {{Flagu|Mandatory Palestine}} 1946, 22 July: The [[King David Hotel bombing]] by Zionist paramilitary group [[Irgun]] kills 91 and injures 46 non-fatally.<ref>[[Thurston Clarke|Clarke, Thurston]]. ''By Blood and Fire'', G. P. Puttnam's Sons, New York, 1981</ref>\n*{{Flagu|Romania}} 1947, 25 July: Three [[Romanian people|Romanian]] terrorists kill an aircrew member aboard a Romanian airliner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Administrator Pistole's remarks before the American Bar Association's 6th Annual Homeland Security Law Institute |date=3 March 2011 |last=Pistole |first=John S. |url=http://www.tsa.gov/press/speeches/030311_dhs_law_institute.shtm |publisher=[[Transportation Security Administration|TSA]] |accessdate=2011-08-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812223620/http://www.tsa.gov/press/speeches/030311_dhs_law_institute.shtm |archivedate=12 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This is regarded as the first aircraft hijack resulting in a fatality.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* {{Flagu|Mandatory Palestine}} 1948, 22 February, [[Ben Yehuda Street bombings]]: three British Army trucks led by an armoured car driven by Arab irregulars and British deserters exploded on Ben Yehuda Street killing 58 Jewish civilians and injuring 140.<ref>Larry Collins and Dominique Lapierre, 'O Jerusalem'.History Book Club. 1972. pages 191-195</ref><ref>Dov Joseph, 'The Faithful City \u2013 The siege of Jerusalem, 1948'. Simon and Schuster, New York. 1960. Library of Congress number: 60-10976. page 37. 'it was possible ... (that the) drivers (were) from the more than two hundred deserters who had already joined the Arab force' (as opposed to being officially sanctioned by the British Army).</ref>\n*{{flag|Philippines|1936}} 1949, 7 May: thirteen people are killed as a Philippine airliner explodes in flight travelling from [[Daet, Camarines Norte|Daet]] to [[Manila]]. A time bomb detonates 30 minutes after departure near [[Alabat Island]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pair Admits Planting Bomb That Killed 13|date=3 June 1949|work=The Telegraph-Herald|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Lk5hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BXUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4037,5415273|accessdate=2013-01-06}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Syria}} 1949, 5 August: 12 killed and dozens injured in the [[Menarsha synagogue attack]], [[Damascus]].\n\n==1950\u20131969==\n* {{Flag|Argentina}} 1953, 15 April: Detonation of two bombs in a union act organized by the [[General Confederation of Labour (Argentina)|General Confederation of Labour]] in [[Plaza de Mayo]] and the [[Plaza de Mayo (Buenos Aires Underground)|Plaza de Mayo stse their hostages and return to Argentina for trial.<ref name=\"La Izquierda Diario\">{{Cite web|